  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>HAND OF THE HAMMERS, PART II</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>“But…”</p>

<p>“But nothing! Daughter, I will not have this talk with you again. You start your training here today, and that is that!” He pointed towards the door of the Chantry of Justice behind him.</p>

<p>“Papa! I want to be a warrior!” The little Barbarian put her fists on her hips and scowled up at her father. “I want to wear armor, and swing a big sword, and…”</p>

<p>“URSI!” Eban roared, shaking snow from the shingles of the building. “You will take yourself inside that chantry. You will do your family proud. And that is the end of the matter.”</p>

<p>Eban stalked off, leaving his daughter fuming in the snow. How could he! Weeks, months, years even, she had stood just outside the practices in the arena, watching and mimicking the moves taught to the warriors. She had spoken to their finest, had brought water to their guildmaster, all in the hopes of someday joining the Wolves of the North. And now, at her fathers seemingly cruel whim, it was all denied her, leaving her to be a…. She could barely even think the word. Shaman.</p>

<p>The polite cough of a cleared throat behind her interrupted her brooding. She’d been ignoring the boy standing there. He leaned against the wall and cleaned his fingernails with a knife, doing his level best to look unruffled and quietly menacing. Privately, she thought he looked silly. He’d tried to creep quietly up during the argument with her father, but all the daggers he wore strapped about him and his too-big armor made more noise than a herd of mammoths in full stampede.</p>

<p>“You can’t be a warrior, you know,” he said, voice overly casual. “Uncle says that girls can’t be warriors. They’re too soft to swing anything but a frying pan well.”</p>

<p>And that was the final straw. Snarling like an angry wolf, Ursi launched herself at the boy, catching him off guard. They tumbled to the snow with a loud crash, rolling over and kicking up the mud beneath the frost. As the momentum wore off Ursi sat atop the boy, pounding her fist into his face and shrieking incoherent epithets about “soft” and “boys” and other things best left unmentioned.</p>

<p>An unexpected right hook caught her in the face and she toppled back to the ground. The boy flung himself onto her, kicking and punching and gouging, ill-fitting armor shedding like a dog’s winter coat. By now, a crowd was beginning to gather, watching the pair with unveiled amusement. Off to the side, the banker began taking bets quietly.</p>

<p>Finally a pair of burly warriors pulled the children apart before they did each other permanent harm. Chuckling, one of the shamans took Ursi inside, handing her a handkerchief to stop her bloody nose. The guildleader sighed and shook his head. “Do you have all that out of your system now?”</p>

<p>“I dob wadt noo be a shaban!” she said, the cloth in her nostril somewhat diminishing the authority of the statement. “I wadt noo be a warbior!”</p>

<p>He snorted. “And why do you want to be a warrior, little bear? They’re smelly and not the brightest fireflies in the swarm.”</p>

<p>“Dey are nobt!” She pulled the handkerchief out of her nose. “They are not! They can fight, and win battles!”</p>

<p>“Aye, they do. But even the finest warrior will die if he has no healer at his back to mend his wounds and cure the poisons used by his enemies.”</p>

<p>“Warriors wear armor! They look big and scary in it!” She crossed her arms defiantly.</p>

<p>He tapped the greenish breastplate he wore. “Shamans wear armor. Special totemic armor that we must fight horrible beasts for, instead of simply having it made like the warriors do.”</p>

<p>“Well…uhm…warriors get to swing big swords!” Triumphantly, she smirked.</p>

<p>From behind him, the guildmaster pulled out a feathered and beaded staff that stood as tall as he did. “Shamans use weapons far larger than the biggest of the warriors’ swords.” As Ursi stood blinking, he continued. “Let me tell you what else shamans do that warriors do not, small bear. Shamans heal, ‘tis true, but we do more than that.</p>

<p>“We are the casters of curses, the callers of plagues. Our magics bring our enemies low, weakening them and leaving them defenseless. Where a warrior pummels, we use our heads. Where a warrior stands and dies alone, we summon a companion to aid us that we may live.”</p>

<p>Reaching out, he traced the hammer symbol that hung on the wall. “My dear child, we are the bringers of Justice. The Hands of the Hammers. The judgers of mankind. We have been charged with the sacred duty of the Tribunal, to see that Justice is always done. And this is a far larger responsibility than most warriors are ever given. Only the strongest, the wisest, and the bravest are called to this duty. Would you really turn it down?”</p>

<p>Awed, she shook her head. “N-no, I guess I wouldn’t.”</p>

<p>Kindly, he grinned down at her. “I thought not. Let me show you then, young friend, your new home.”</p>

<p>By the end of her tour, Ursi felt nearly excited at her future. “Are you ready to begin?” asked the guildmaster.</p>

<p>“Oh, yes!” she exclaimed, pushing an unruly lock of hair out of her face and wincing as she touched a bruise.</p>

<p>“I’m glad to hear it,” he said, handing her a rolled parchment. “Here is your first spell. Once you have copied that into the spellbook I gave you and have learned its use, you will go out into the world to practice your combat skills a bit. It is our practice to pair our younger members with a youth from another trade, that you may learn to work as a team and make up for each other’s weaknesses.”</p>

<p>He beckoned towards the door. In walked a boy, his eye newly purple and his split lip swelling. She scowled at him, and he glowered right back. “Khaleb here will be your partner….” His voice trailed off into an amused chuckle. “I see that you’ve already met.” The chuckles turned to laughter as the glares deepened. “I think that you both have interesting times ahead.”</p>

<p>Truer words had never been spoken.</p> </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Ursi</b> Submited on 3/9/2001</small></td>
